---

ðŸ§© What .reduce() Does

Definition:
.reduce() takes an array and reduces it down to a single value (like sum, average, object, or even another array).

It does this by running a function on each element â€” where the result of one iteration is passed to the next as an accumulator.


---

ðŸ§  Syntax

array.reduce((accumulator, currentValue, index, array) => {
  // return updated accumulator
}, initialValue);

Parameters:

Name	Meaning

accumulator	Stores the running result (starts as initialValue)
currentValue	The current element in the array
index	Current index (optional)
array	The entire array (optional)
initialValue	The value from which reduction starts



---

ðŸ§® Example 1 â€” Sum of all numbers

const arr = [10, 20, 30, 40];

const total = arr.reduce((acc, curr) => {
  return acc + curr;
}, 0);

console.log(total);  // Output: 100

How it works step-by-step:

Step	acc (accumulator)	curr (currentValue)	Returned

1	0	10	10
2	10	20	30
3	30	30	60
4	60	40	100


ðŸ‘‰ After looping through all elements, .reduce() returns 100.


---

ðŸ§  Example 2 â€” Without initial value

If you omit the second argument (0 in this case),
then the first element of the array becomes the initial accumulator,
and reduce starts from the second element.

const total = arr.reduce((acc, curr) => acc + curr);
console.log(total);  // Still 100

But âš  this can cause issues on empty arrays â€” so usually, we give an explicit initial value (like 0).


---

ðŸ§  Example 3 â€” Using index and array (optional)

const arr = [1, 2, 3, 4];

const result = arr.reduce((acc, curr, index, array) => {
  console.log(Step ${index}: acc = ${acc}, curr = ${curr});
  return acc + curr;
}, 0);

console.log(result);

âœ… Youâ€™ll see how the accumulator grows step by step.


---

ðŸ§  Example 4 â€” Build something else (like object)

You can even use .reduce() to create objects, not just numbers.

const fruits = ['apple', 'banana', 'apple', 'orange', 'banana', 'apple'];

const count = fruits.reduce((acc, fruit) => {
  if (acc[fruit]) {
    acc[fruit]++;
  } else {
    acc[fruit] = 1;
  }
  return acc;
}, {});

console.log(count);
// Output: { apple: 3, banana: 2, orange: 1 }


---

ðŸ’¡ Quick Summary

Concept	Description

.map()	Creates a new array (same length)
.filter()	Creates a new array (shorter)
.reduce()	Reduces the array to a single result (any type)
Returns	Whatever you return from the last iteration
Modifies original?	âŒ No



---

ðŸª„ Shortcut Example

const arr = [2, 4, 6];
const sum = arr.reduce((a, b) => a + b, 0);
console.log(sum); // 12


